data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already didn't support sync operations natively — you opted in to **sync-over-async** (blocking on async calls internally). In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), **that opt-in is removed entirely**.

Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

### The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key points

1. **All callers must go async too** — `async` propagates up the call stack, so controllers/services that call these methods need `async Task<IActionResult>`, etc.
2. **Remove the old opt-in config** — the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` or `ConfigureWarnings` suppression for sync Cosmos calls will no longer compile or will be ignored.
3. **`Add()` stays sync** — entity tracking (`Add`, `Remove`, `Attach`) is in-memory and remains synchronous. Only query execution and `SaveChanges` need the async switch.
